In this context of global environmental changes, many invasive plants are clonal organisms (
 Liu et al., 2006; 
 Keser et al., 2014), and their longevity is an important demographic trait for understanding the life history, population dynamics, ecology and evolutionary fitness of plant species, (
 Harper, 1977; 
 Schmid, 1990; 
 Silvertown, 1991). Long-lived plant clones have been documented in various aquatic and wetland ecosystems (
 Santamar√≠a, 2002). The asexual reproduction of clonal growth results in size expansion of genets and increased fitness as greater floral production in larger clones increases the potential for outcrossing and sexual reproduction (
 Barrett, 2015). Extreme longevity of clonal species allow genets to persist through periods with environmental conditions when sexual reproduction is rare or precluded. Clonality is a survival strategy of plant species that may support longevity at millennial timescales and through rapid global environmental changes (
 Bricker et al., 2018).
